Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A madhouse where young people meet.
A graveyard chapel where they're now digging for the subway tunnel.
Small gardeners are maintaining the old farming land.
The oldest official map of Munich promotes exciting stories.
It's annoying when maps aren't up to date.
Anyone who's ever had to get upset about that knows that because the auto-navi was showing a green lawn instead of a bypass.
The historical maps of the digital Bavarian atlas, an offer from the Bavarian government's geoportal, are far from current - but very informative.
Especially when you compare them to current online maps.
It then becomes clear how cities and communities in the Munich Mercury area have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavarian atlas is a rug that is not immediately recognized as such.
The large overview map incorporated more detailed maps for cities and municipalities, called urposition sheets.
These were created according to the Bavarian survey administration between 1810 and 1864 and stem from the first survey of Bavaria.
Your client is Napoleon.
The French army commander occupied Bavaria from the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical survey of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even though the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was the neighbors of today who created the idea of a comprehensive Bavarian map.
Crown Prince Max IV Joseph carried the project forward, founding the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Investigation Administration.
The Munich Urposition is from 1856 and, like all others, can be found on the Bavarian State Library website.
The comparison between the past and the present is most impressive in the example of the capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is the sub-sendling, which appears in the 1856 map still relatively isolated.
Sendling was incorporated as a borough of Munich 21 years after the map was drawn up, in 1877.
Today, the underground is in the middle of the city.
The houses of the Unterendlings are concentrated around 1856 along the present Plinganserstraße, which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasant uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where the West Park is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance, when you zoom in, a smaller map appears with dozens of lines and numbers: hand-numbered floors from the so-called "grabbing", from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots of land are no longer occupied by farmers - they are occupied by small gardeners of the Land in the Sun.
A large green area is drawn north of Subendling.
The Theresienweide, the site of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was actually a weed in the 19th century - not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives a glimpse into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the opening page of the newspaper, in the territory of the present-day district of Au-Haidhausen, the street name is not only "am Gasteig" or "On the Airs" - but also "Irren Anstalten" in large letters.
Yes, on Auerfeldstraße, people with delusions were once locked up.
In 1858/59 the Munich Circle of the "Auf der Uhr Luft" (On the Hours of the Wind) was founded.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institute - the psychiatrist who is brought in connection with the death of King Louis II.
"He was progressive for his time, ending, for example, the chain of so-called fools.
He also prohibited the use of force against the inmates", says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Haidhausen Museum, which has been working with the institute for an exhibition.
Initially, 280 patients could be accommodated, but later it was expanded to 500.
At some point, this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Circular Centre in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost has been located there, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany.
On the grounds of the former Auer Anstalts, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities.
To the west is the football field of the TSV Munich East, to the east are 1980s residential buildings.
In 2015, the children's home "Casa Don Bosco" was built - based on the original construction of the insane asylum, which was destroyed by bombing during World War II.
The Marienplatz was registered as "Main Platz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
Allied bombs in December 1944 tore many holes in the city center.
One big one stayed until today - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business houses and a medieval tomb chapel once stood at Marienhof, where the preparatory work and the spat staging for the second S-Bahn main line take place on 5 April 2017.
The slide controller can compare the old Munich map with today's aerial view - and fill the hole at Marienhof.
Civil Rights group publishes travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning for people of color who travel to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is scheduled to take effect on August 28, 2017, urges African American travelers, visitors and Missourians to exercise special caution and extreme caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable racial-based incidents have recently occurred and are being noted throughout the state", the group said in a statement.
A recent Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as state law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"They have civil rights violations that people are going through.
They're being stopped because of their skin color, they're being beaten up or killed", Missouri NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints in such frequency as we have never heard before".
It's the first such warning the organization has issued to a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racial abuse against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas during his trip across the state and being taken into custody by Missouri State Police without charge of a crime.
The council also points to a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office that shows black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites in the state.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People must be prepared to bring bail or let their relatives know they're traveling through the state".
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, which ranks the state 16th in the nation in terms of the number of such crimes.
The travel advisory is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently, interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
