Nothing is sacred anymore?
Now the White House of Trump is taking the Statue of Liberty
The most sure sign of a regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
The Americans appreciate this as much as any other - hence the carefully staged fall of Saddam Hussein in Firdo Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, surely knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with Jim Acosta of CNN over the president's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller didn't attack the statue himself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty imitators would have lynched him if he had.
But he addressed its significance, and in particular the significance attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its foundation in 1903, 17 years after the memorial was completed.
As Miller slandered Acosta, "I don't want to go into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you're referring to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty".
Miller is right, but as he put it, it's not really about history.
It is a contemporary echo of Lazarus's stirring words, the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants but the poorest of the poor: "Your fatigue, your poverty, your distressed masses who long to breathe freely, the miserable waste of your rich coasts".
There was never a time when the "poor waste" was better visible on our screens.
Miller didn't engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's United States.
This conflict over the significance of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural debate: it is indeed a conflict over the significance of America.
Lazarus and her friends, who were committed to putting their words on the ground after her death, knew very well that they were committing a high-level political act.
The sculpture was to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the poem: the female figure is no longer abstract - she has a voice.
And she gives herself a very different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The poem's connection to the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativity.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right-wingers have long wanted to change that.
The great trumpetist Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist for Trump's coming, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative that brought the American flame into the night world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
She's supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch should not light the way to the United States".
It's rather unusual that Limbaugh came across something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of perception.
Lazarus' great imaginative act was to see her as she was seen by the tired, miserable, but hopeful people after long and often dreadful journeys on the decks of ships.
It's really about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that's not the perspective Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch should not light the way, but ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
