Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand the excitement of voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for the newspapers to beat him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
He was a critic, I'm sure.
But he didn't silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away, and, stupid and mute, we're being led to the slaughter like sheep".
That brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan, who has to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's employees have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their views on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week for that.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online comment was filled with a backlash with, "Well, what?"
"It's just Facebook", many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important if it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state that is amazingly popular.
He has the second highest approval rating among the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in leading his state and strict adherence to the principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as a primary means to connect with his constituents and to debut his hairless head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's side - which is a public forum, which is officially called, and by employees who are paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions and argued that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people whipping online.
The mail spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not profane.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his mail and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she was asking about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other news", she wrote in the comment section of The Post.
"I also disapprove of this idea, if a number of people take a stand on the same issue, then they are more likely to be disregarded by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of concerned citizens".
What the governor's staff called a "focused spam attack" would likely be called "primitive language".
The Facebook era makes it easy to cut a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than in the past, if you'd done the same thing, sending staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical articles or arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally right now.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for slandering Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones in this matter came in Virginia last week.
The chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she removed a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable port had a similar effect to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers joined his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
People who used pseudonyms like "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Portius" wrote all the letters to newspapers that were downplaying Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Amity Treaty, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he didn't silence her.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
