Poverty and Death in the Indonesian Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually places a sweet potato - locally called a "note" - right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred lump is removed and swallowed with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with cloudy water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m"., she says.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia when only 1,026 elders were to vote in public hand-pollination before the occupying forces.
An existing movement that was fighting for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control over the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is boring, and the trip includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital, Jayapura, to Nabire, followed by a 5-hour rental car ride each morning.
There is no public transportation.
The city of about 19,000 people is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and wavy roofs that have been rusted to various yellow-brown tones.
Very few Indonesians have made their journey here, let alone journalists and practically no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, pointing to her vibrant hand-woven turban, her dark shirt, and her bright skirt.
"We used to have only leaves on our bodies".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28 percent of the population living below the poverty line and some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuan people, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papua's demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden geese and are treated mercilessly.
Activists say more than 500,000 Papuan people have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in the Papuan tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
In the region alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We're gonna lose everything", says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities from the previous year, such as illegal executions and torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week", says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been strengthened as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographic developments are changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the densely populated islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a vegetable mixed with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to stay here.
"Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at a lower price than the local Papuan market", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura to work.
"It cost the native Papuan - the mama-mama [the women] of Papua - their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, pledged to address inequalities and violations of the law in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's 29 counties - including Paniai - en route to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, expecting him to fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored", You says.
In fact, Paniai suffered a low just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols in front of a camp fire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offense at her tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers who had been drinking, chasing and hitting the group with their rifle bullets, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
A child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field outside the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird's song - of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military posts.
As the mood picked up, the soldiers received an order from an internal radio: "If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them to death", says an official TIME document that was not released to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, saw the threat and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was shot in my left wrist", he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired, but he says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired", he adds.
The local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", said Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, has only one name, to TIME in a gloomy mood.
"I saw he was dead... I kissed him".
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers only wanted their station "safe" because it was being attacked.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us", said Papua Police spokesman, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
The news of the killings was not "filtered" to Jakarta until the next day.
For three weeks, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the victims' families and vowing to address the historic abuses in Papua.
"I want this case resolved immediately so that it will not happen again in the future", he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Wiranto said that he was establishing an extrajudicial mechanism to remedy historic human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most injuries have been reported long ago.
Some were in the '90s and early 2000s.
