New results of the Swedish Asylum Age Assessment Tests published
The latest results of tests on asylum seekers in Sweden, which have been subjected to a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80 percent of those tested are over 18. But not everyone believes the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started conducting the tests last year.
They are to make the age assessment more accurate during the asylum procedure after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationverket) was criticized for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18 years of age".
The tests shall be carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics from the past few months, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases that "suggest that the person being tested was 18 years of age or older".
When the Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that he would be 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which uses X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints and is then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
One skeptic is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think that kind of measurement should be used.
Assessing biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is low.
The greatest risk is if the person is under 18, in which case it is about 10 percent".
