Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a series of HIV medicines taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there are just enough drugs in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medicines can be taken every day or as early as two hours before intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been treated successfully.
In clinics, appropriate participants who agree to the study are identified, including men, women, transgender individuals and those who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also register for a possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will be £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence as it is targeted, recorded and implemented on a large scale.
