Now, researchers have discovered that the first findings of the incredible rhinoceros of a Canadian miner have been so well preserved that experts have described it as "the dinosaur's Mona Lisa".
It was so well preserved that they could even tell that his skin was reddish brown and they said she had something of a "disturbed past".
A report in Current Biology called it "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world".
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived between 110 million and 112 million years ago in the middle Cretaceous.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has amazed researchers who describe it as "really remarkable".
According to reports in National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best preserved fossil of its kind.
It was discovered by Shawn Funk while digging in the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed missing from the surrounding rock in the square, and decided to look closer.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
They spent the next six years trying to uncover the wild animal within the 1,100-pound [2,500 kg] earth cluster.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
"If you blink a little, you could almost believe it was asleep", said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature can be seen.
"It will go down in science history as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of the Dinosaurs".
Researchers have found that this herbivore, although covered in armor and resembling a moving tank, was likely threatened by flesh-eating dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used a red and white cloak to hide from predators, and it used a shielding technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend better into its environment and avoid its enemies, experts say, suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110 million-year-old creature from the Nodosaur family made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Now researchers have studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that has spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of shells and armor on his body.
They discovered the counter shading, a common method of defense in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although the contrasting effect is common, the results are surprising, since the size of borealopelta far exceeds that of the animals living today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was hunted by enough pressure from flesh-eating dinosaurs that evolution favored the disguise of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most of the contemporary animals that use the countershading -- think of reindeer, zebras, or belts -- are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, which signals that this nodosaur was in a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous must have been", Brown said.
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was red-brown.
Scientists continue to examine the animal for evidence of its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was driven out into the sea, where it sank to the bottom of the sea on its back.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida today, and rivers and oceans probably spread farther inland than they do today.
"This Nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved shallow skin, but it also remains in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal", Brown said.
"The result is that the animal looks almost as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don't need much imagination to reconstruct it. If you just blink a little, you could almost believe he's asleep".
The Cretaceous was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, traversed the earth.
Although their king, Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors.
Among them is the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot-long, six-ton monster.
Scientists whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology believe that Borealopelta was sunk into the sea after death and mummified in the mud.
