How did an activist learn the answer to the question, "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just one day after she arrived in New York City, the St. Louis native was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolling through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a mail from someone from high school.
"Police just killed an 18-year-old child, and he's still lying on the street", it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis area rapper was tweeting live the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street and would stay there for four hours.
"This is wild", Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to them or their community.
She put down her phone to tweet about people on the Canfield drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police band and people screaming, and a man claiming to be Brown's father, who was wearing a sign that said, "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!"
She was watching a live feed where a police officer was standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another cop disarmed his rifle and shouted, "I'm gonna kill you... animals all".
"That's not common", Ferrell recalled.
"This is not the kind of murder we're used to and can call typical".
At that moment, I felt a tremor of frost.
I was angry and I cried".
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?" in theaters starting on the 11th.
It's a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, from the perspective of people living in the community who have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and a matching crown, the two had a conversation they had countless times before that morning about the black experience and the black condition.
"Remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take her with me", Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a culmination of what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well-developed, not only activism and organization, but also the different layers of black experience and black constitution and what we need to do to become free to free ourselves.
Even though I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't personally experience blatant racism, she's no different than the next black woman's child.
I feel like I would be doing her a bad service to keep her away from it".
The first station they arrived at in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place opposite the police station that became a campground as activists waited for Officer Darren Wilson's possible non-accusation.
Ferrell and her daughter met a local business owner who was cooking lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters.
Slowly, a new kind of activism for Ferrell began to take shape.
"My activism has changed completely since August 9", she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come to pass".
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the co-directors of the film.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar were just trying to "document" what happened.
A question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or try to find a story that you can use?"
This skepticism has been nurtured by countless instances of people, often whites, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently explained in an interview, "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn't center their voices, and we wanted to do it differently".
Folayan had already collaborated with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist in the field known for his activism around death row inmates.
His commitment brought Ferrell closer to the project, and along with six other locals, the Whose Streets team followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or talks to us.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people were portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed".
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement "is not about a Messianic leader, but a community coming together", Folayan said - she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, "Whose Streets" documents reveal surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life as he falls in love and marries his wife.
"I felt like naked", Ferrell said, laughing when she saw the finished product for the first time.
"But I've come to understand that there must be some vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people".
In addition, Ferrell's story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement who shaped the social media film "BlacklivesMatter" after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement overall", Ferrell said, "and so we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of everything".
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being sustained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action" in which Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up that energy", she said.
"It's no coincidence that she was on the front lines, because there's so much at stake in a life at these crossroads as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen".
Meanwhile, the news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared, but the racial ties between the community and the police still exist.
Ferrell is on probation for two and a half years for blocking a freeway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area, which she calls her home, "a chaos".
Yet she's been clinging to a song and she's been committed to that memory ever since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains".
