A fitting resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York City, you can see many faces - white, black, and brown, almost unremarkably similar - hanging from cables on the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek-tapping and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the excerpts from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence after making public classified diplomatic communications via the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and groundbreaking dissident whose conviction was overturned by Barack Obama when he was only three days into office.
Dewey-Hagborg, by using the algorithmic analysis of DNA extracted by Manning and created from the 30 portraits of what someone with this genomic data might look like, has created a sharp, if intellectual, commentary not only on the formability of DNA data - the many ways in which it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since her teens, was convicted in 2013 of 20 counts, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud and theft.
The prison had suppressed her image so much that there was only one photo - a grainy, black and white selfie, in which Manning was sitting uncomfortable in a wheelchair wearing a platinum blonde wig - that she was associated with.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was just returning from the huge success of her 2012 project Stranger Visions.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That's when she got an email from a newspaper magazine.
"They were interviewing Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some kind of portrait to accompany this article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press briefing of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't be visited at the time, and she couldn't be photographed, so you contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to do a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequal correspondence friends who exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic strip by Shoili Kanungo called "Suppressed Images", which predicted a future where President Chelsea would change her decision and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually demand Manning's release a few days after the book was published after seven brutal years in a Kansas military prison was a welcome kind of happy reunion.
There's something deep and strong about the opening of the exhibition, too, as Donald Trump wages a war against government informants and transgender troops to find new, two-way ways to further ignite the rigid divisions he was supposed to resolve.
When Dewey-Hagborg was asked about the strange timing of all these things, she said, "Things happen for a reason".
In an artistic statement written on the gallery wall, Manning, with her oversized signature below (the "i" in her family name is a heart) called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation that has been based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture".
On the opposite wall is their mitochondrial DNA sequence -- a thousand-foot of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
Dewey-Hagborg hoped to show by incorporating the 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's highly developed scientific lexicon) how amazingly similar, at least biologically, we are all.
"What people are hoping to take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Spurious Memories, is also on view.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so that's 30 of those stories".
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in a private room, is a page from the comic novel mentioned above.
It shows Manning emerging from the United States disciplinary barracks with a free-speech phone in her hand, like King Kong.
"If they keep your speech cold, they win", they say.
"So never shut up".
"It came straight from a letter she wrote me", said the Philadelphia-based artist.
"I still get goose bumps when I talk about it".
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition in person yet - as was predicted in the comic book - but if she does, she'll be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, by her own genomic simulators, gathering like hordes of protesters.
This was also targeted, like everything in the exhibition, down to the size (5" 2, Manning's stature) where their genetic haplogroups were written with pencil.
"In the past I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd", Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that was formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was behind their release".
