"We will conclude the WADA Roadmap in the near future" - Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not be long before the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) for the restoration of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) were implemented.
'At a certain stage of meeting the criteria of the roadmap, RUSADA has been granted the right to plan and test in cooperation with UKAD (UK Anti-Doping).
The WADA roadmap has been updated in this respect", Mutko said on Thursday.
The PM commented on the second part of the WADA Roadmap for Compliance with the Code, which describes the criteria for the re-establishment of RUSADA and was recently published on the organisation's website.
According to Mutko, it contains nothing that could cause Russia to worry.
"Everything has been announced, everything is being implemented.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future", he added.
However, one of the criteria listed in the list states that the Russian anti-doping authorities must publicly accept the reported results of the WADA-approved investigation by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren into alleged state-sponsored doping in Russian sport.
In relation to the matter, Mutko said: "We are conducting the investigation because our anti-doping system has admitted an error.
All measures have been implemented.
But there were no government programs, and we will not admit anything that does not exist".
Mutko's words were in agreement with those of Vitaly Smirnov, the head of the independent Russian Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russian retail outlet RSport earlier in the day, Smirnov admitted past problems in Russian anti-doping organizations, but then added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one intends to accept this report unconditionally", Smirnov added.
In November 2015, RUSADA was excluded from conducting doping controls in Russia by WADA in the wake of the doping scandal.
However, it was allowed to plan and coordinate tests under the supervision of international experts and the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
After a visit to the organization's headquarters in Moscow in July, WADA Director-General Olivier Niggli stated that RUSADA was "moving in the right direction" to be re-commissioned.
