The start-ups that will help your business not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to test your employee's happiness in your e-commerce startup, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or - worse - deceitful.
And even if you promised anonymity, some workers didn't trust the process.
"There was just never consistency and objectivity", said Errett, who runs the 75-person San Francisco e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed.
She's been calling out for help.
A new breed of HR start-ups is growing to help companies figure out how their employees feel.
By creating and licensing software that has the specific purpose of measuring employee engagement, it enables companies to conduct surveys, address specific groups and demographics, provide employee anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases, allows whistleblowers to bypass C-Suite executives and contact the board directly.
"You now have tools like Strava and Fitbit to track your health, but where is Fitbit for your business?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and chief executive of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained a better insight into what your employees think and feel in the three years with Glint.
In addition to the snap surveys and surveys of specific teams, it provides a company heat map that shows at a glance which units have the most complaints and which executives have low approval ratings - so you can dig up why.
Companies are coming to realize that they need to stay on top of workplace culture so they don't become the next Uber to be involved in scandal since a former employee posted a blog post describing an environment of harassment where those who spoke were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire for a review is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to the financial technology website Let's Talk Payments.
Denver, Colorado, startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid the Uber miscredit case.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send tailored "pulse" surveys, collect confidential answers in real time, and view the heat maps of your problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the CEO is involved, complaints go directly to the Supervisory Board.
"The court of public opinion has caught up with the regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, the founder and CEO of Convercent.
When a company is found to be treating its employees badly or behaving unethically, it can experience costly consequences from consumer boycotts, employee fluctuations and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, the restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees and over 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees are aware of the policies and procedures and have an easy way to reach their corporate headquarters.
