Creating a comic novel: a castle in the history of England
In its recent past, the small Scotney Castle was featured in a squeeze music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has experienced 700 years of turbulent history from his comfortable seat in the Bewl River Valley in Kent and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mofo-haired Yorkshireman with a fondness for historical documents.
"I find it so beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years", he says in painful tone.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand".
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardes and documents the families who lived in Scotney, each story illustrated by another emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It's not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I only reacted to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent working for the Jacobins in the 1700's", he says.
"This is his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because that's when you started a fire because of the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has an effect as if he were in it.
I love the archives!"
For someone who is so beaten with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and has lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest: I overestimated my welcome a little bit") all this seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing the archives, and studying the many treasures and curiosities of the castle, such as the mounted hyenas' heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the ditch.
He walked through the grounds and ruins of the old castle, talking to landscapers, gardeners, and sometimes even the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then, at night, he drank "whiskey and started writing".
The intimate history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not receive full access until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff was just beginning to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years of aristocrats saying, 'Oh, throw it to the attic.'
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You might think land conflicts would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a brick that the two families fought for.
Guys, let it go!"
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into English history on a broader basis, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant uprising of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that took place in the castle in 1380, in this book entitled 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,'" says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising began in this area, and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Maybe they're connected?"
Other stories are deeply rooted in the castle's history - such as "The Priest", which tells the story of the Jesuit father who the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery made years later when his coffin was excavated).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favourite family from Scotney: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking boys with a talent for promoting wives".
After completing his assignment at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a comic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th-century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave again", he says.
It was like, "Oh, now I have to deal with the fucking life again".
