Red meat, dairy products and chocolate could help alleviate IBD
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare to your digestive system.
But a new study claims the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could relieve the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, affecting some 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
While people are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microbes that hide in food do not enter the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too far in the direction of inflammation, it can result in inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that a type of tolerance-boosting immune cell is found in mice that carry a specific bacterium in their intestines.
And the bacteria need tryptophan -- one of the building blocks of proteins -- to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between a bacterial species - Lactobacillus reuteri - that is a normal part of the gut microbiome and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their food, the more of these immune cells they had".
He suggested that combining L. reuteri and a diet high in tryptophan would promote a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment if the same system worked in humans.
Postdoctoral fellow Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan studied a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same tribe, which was separately housed, did not.
She suspected that the difference was because of the gut microbiomes of mice -- the community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were DNA sequenced and there were six types of bacteria found that were present in the mice with the immune cells, but were missing in the mice without them.
Mice were raised in a sterile environment, so they lacked a gut microbiome and they didn't develop this kind of immune cells, and they got the L. reuteri and they got the immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells evolved into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active ingredient was cleared from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the tryptophan metabolism known as Indol-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuterium in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop cells in humans as in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said, "The development of these cells is probably something we want to promote, because these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may potentially lead to an expansion of this population.'
